===Etymology===
* First attested in mid 15th century.
* From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|acrewen|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|acreue|acreüe|lang=fro}}, past participle of {{term|accreistre||to increase|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term/t|la|accrēsco||increase}}, from {{term|ad||in addition|lang=la}} + {{term/t|la|crēscō||to grow}}.
* Compare [[accretion]], [[accresce]], [[accrete]], [[crew]], [[crescent]].

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK|US}} {{IPA|/əˈkɹuː/|/ə.ˈkɹu/}}
* {{audio|en-us-accrue.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*: {{rhymes|uː}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|accru|ing}}

# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To increase, to [[augment]]; to come to by way of increase; to [[arise]] or spring as a growth or result; to be added as increase, profit, or damage, especially as the produce of money lent.
#* ''And though power failed, her courage did '''accrue''''' - [[w:Edmund Spenser|Edmund Spenser]]
#* ''Interest '''accrues''' to principal'' - [[Abbott]]
#* ''The great and essential advantages '''accruing''' to society from the freedom of the press'' - [[Junius]]
# {{context|intransitive|accounting|lang=en}} To be [[incurred]] as a result of the passage of time.
#: ''The monthly financial statements show all the actual but only some of the '''accrued''' expenses.''
# {{context|intransitive|legal|lang=en}} To become an enforceable and permanent right.

